.TH CRUSHR-FORMAT 5 "February 2026" "crushr 0.1.0" "File Formats"
.SH NAME
crushr-format \- on-disk .crs archive format
.SH OVERVIEW
A .crs file is a sequence of compressed data blocks followed by an index and a footer.
Blocks are zstd frames; the index describes files and maps file extents to blocks.
The footer contains offsets/lengths and cryptographic hashes for verification.
.SH LAYOUT
.nf
[block 0][block 1]...[block N][index][footer]
.fi
.PP
Readers locate the footer at end-of-file, verify the index hash, then can
random-access file extents by seeking into the referenced blocks.
.SH BLOCKS
Each block has a small header and a zstd frame payload. Blocks are independent:
a reader can seek to a block boundary and decompress only that block.
.SH INDEX
The index is a zstd-compressed blob containing:
.IP \(bu 2
a file table (path, mode, mtime, uid/gid, size, xattr references)
.IP \(bu
an extent table mapping file ranges to (block_id, offsets, lengths)
.IP \(bu
optional dictionary metadata
.PP
The index is hashed with BLAKE3 and recorded in the footer.
.SH FOOTER
The footer records:
.IP \(bu 2
offset/length of the index
.IP \(bu
end offset of the last block
.IP \(bu
BLAKE3 hash of the index (and other sections as the format evolves)
.SH VERSIONING
crushr is expected to add new footer and block header versions while preserving
read compatibility with older archives where practical.
